---
import ContentLayout from '../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import { useTranslations } from '../../i18n/ui';

const lang = 'en';
const t = useTranslations(lang);

const structuredData = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'HowTo',
  name: 'How to set up Claude for vibe coding',
  description: t.tools.metaDescription,
  inLanguage: 'en',
  step: [
    {
      '@type': 'HowToStep',
      name: 'Choose a Claude plan',
      text: 'Select between Free, Pro, or Max based on your needs',
    },
    {
      '@type': 'HowToStep',
      name: 'Install Node.js',
      text: 'Download and install Node.js 18 or higher',
    },
    {
      '@type': 'HowToStep',
      name: 'Install Claude Code',
      text: 'Run npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code',
    },
  ],
};
---

<ContentLayout
  title={`${t.tools.title} | ${t.siteTitle}`}
  description={t.tools.metaDescription}
  lang={lang}
  currentPath="tools"
  structuredData={structuredData}
>
  <h1>Tools & Setup</h1>
  <p class="lead">{t.tools.description}</p>

  <nav class="toc">
    <h2>Contents</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="#plans">Claude Plans</a></li>
      <li><a href="#options">Coding Options</a></li>
      <li><a href="#installation">Installing Claude Code</a></li>
      <li><a href="#setup">Recommended Setup</a></li>
    </ul>
  </nav>

  <section id="plans">
    <h2>Claude Plans</h2>

    <p>Anthropic offers several plans based on your needs. Here's an honest breakdown:</p>

    <div class="table-container">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Plan</th>
            <th>Price</th>
            <th>Features</th>
            <th>Recommended for</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Free</strong></td>
            <td>$0</td>
            <td>Limited messages, Claude 3.5 Sonnet</td>
            <td>Testing, simple tasks</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="highlighted">
            <td><strong>Pro</strong></td>
            <td>$20/mo</td>
            <td>5x more usage, Claude 3.5 Opus, priority</td>
            <td>Regular use, serious projects</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Max</strong></td>
            <td>$100/mo</td>
            <td>20x more usage, maximum priority</td>
            <td>Intensive professional use</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Team</strong></td>
            <td>$25/user/mo</td>
            <td>Collaboration, admin controls</td>
            <td>Teams</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Enterprise</strong></td>
            <td>Custom</td>
            <td>SSO, advanced security</td>
            <td>Enterprises</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p><strong>Our recommendation:</strong> For vibe coding we recommend <strong>Claude Pro</strong> - it's the perfect balance between capability and price. The free plan has limits that can frustrate you mid-project.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="options">
    <h2>Coding Options</h2>

    <h3>Option A: Claude.ai (Web)</h3>
    <p>The simplest way to start. You only need a browser.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Pros:</strong> No installation, works on any device</li>
      <li><strong>Cons:</strong> Manual copy/paste of code</li>
      <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Quick questions, learning concepts</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Option B: Claude Code (CLI) - RECOMMENDED</h3>
    <p>Anthropic's official command-line tool. It's the best vibe coding experience.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Pros:</strong> Direct integration with your file system, can read and write code automatically</li>
      <li><strong>Cons:</strong> Requires basic installation</li>
      <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Real projects, the complete vibe coding experience</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Option C: Claude in your IDE</h3>
    <p>Extensions for VS Code and other editors that integrate Claude.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Cursor:</strong> Editor with built-in Claude</li>
      <li><strong>VS Code Extensions:</strong> Various options available</li>
      <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Programmers who already use a specific IDE</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section id="installation">
    <h2>Installing Claude Code</h2>

    <h3>Requirements</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Node.js 18 or higher</strong> - <a href="https://nodejs.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Download from nodejs.org</a></li>
      <li><strong>Terminal:</strong> Windows Terminal, iTerm2 (Mac), or your system terminal</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Step 1: Install Node.js</h3>
    <p>Node.js is required to run Claude Code. Choose the instructions for your operating system:</p>

    <h4>Windows</h4>
    <ol>
      <li>Go to <a href="https://nodejs.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">nodejs.org</a></li>
      <li>Download the LTS installer (big green button)</li>
      <li>Run the downloaded .msi file</li>
      <li>Follow the installation wizard (accept the default options)</li>
      <li>Restart your terminal or PowerShell after installing</li>
    </ol>

    <h4>Mac</h4>
    <p>Option 1 - Using Homebrew (recommended):</p>
    <CodeBlock code={`# If you don't have Homebrew, install it first:
/bin/bash -c "$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Homebrew/install/HEAD/install.sh)"

# Then install Node.js:
brew install node`} language="bash" filename="Terminal" />

    <p>Option 2 - Direct installer:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Go to <a href="https://nodejs.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">nodejs.org</a></li>
      <li>Download the LTS installer for macOS</li>
      <li>Run the .pkg file and follow the instructions</li>
    </ol>

    <h4>Linux (Ubuntu/Debian)</h4>
    <CodeBlock code={`# Update repositories
sudo apt update

# Install Node.js from official repository
curl -fsSL https://deb.nodesource.com/setup_lts.x | sudo -E bash -
sudo apt install -y nodejs`} language="bash" filename="Terminal" />

    <h4>Linux (Fedora/RHEL)</h4>
    <CodeBlock code={`# Install Node.js
sudo dnf install nodejs`} language="bash" filename="Terminal" />

    <p><strong>Verify the installation</strong> (all systems):</p>
    <CodeBlock code={`node --version
npm --version`} language="bash" filename="Terminal" />
    <p>You should see version numbers like <code>v18.x.x</code> or higher.</p>

    <h3>Step 2: Install Claude Code</h3>
    <p>Open your terminal and run:</p>
    <CodeBlock code="npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code" language="bash" filename="Terminal" />

    <p>On Mac with Homebrew you can also use:</p>
    <CodeBlock code="brew install claude-code" language="bash" filename="Terminal" />

    <h3>Step 3: Verify installation</h3>
    <CodeBlock code="claude --version" language="bash" filename="Terminal" />

    <h3>Step 4: First use</h3>
    <p>Simply type <code>claude</code> in your terminal:</p>
    <CodeBlock code="claude" language="bash" filename="Terminal" />

    <p>The first time it will ask you to log in with your Anthropic account. Follow the on-screen instructions.</p>

    <div class="callout callout-success">
      <p><strong>Done!</strong> You can now start vibe coding. Go to your project folder and type <code>claude</code> to begin.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="setup">
    <h2>Recommended Setup</h2>

    <h3>Terminal</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Windows:</strong> Windows Terminal (comes with Windows 11, downloadable for Windows 10)</li>
      <li><strong>Mac:</strong> iTerm2 or the native Terminal</li>
      <li><strong>Linux:</strong> Your favorite terminal</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Editor (Optional)</h3>
    <p>Although Claude Code can create and edit files, it's useful to have an editor to review the code:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>VS Code</strong> - Free and very popular</li>
      <li><strong>Cursor</strong> - VS Code with built-in AI</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Version Control</h3>
    <p><strong>Git</strong> is essential for any project. It allows you to:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Save versions of your code</li>
      <li>Undo changes if something goes wrong</li>
      <li>Collaborate with others</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="next-section">
      <a href="/en/first-app" class="btn btn-primary btn-large">
        Next: Your First App â†’
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</ContentLayout>

